Introduction

  1. Forecasting the occurrence and non-occurrence of any disease is crucial in disease management. It requires long experimental procedures and non-outbreak prediction are not explored. Timely prediction of disease happenings could support effective implementation of preventative measures through early detection of disease outbreaks and non-outbreaks, providing valuable insights for mitigation strategies of novel diseases. (gao2025early?)

  2. In Bayesian inference, all unknowns—observable (data) as well as unobservables (parameters and auxiliary variables)—are considered to be random and assigned probability distributions.These distributions best summarize the available information, and Bayesian inference then updates prior knowledge about the unobservables with information about them contained in the data. The prior distribution and likelihood function are both necessary parts of a Bayesian analysis. Depending on the strength of information contained in the measurements, the prior distribution may or may not influence the outcome or parts thereof. (Klauenberg2015?)

  3. Using a Bayesian approach, This study projected the increase in the rates of Atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (ASCVD) in Asian countries. Given the significant personal and societal burden, the study aimed to accurately forecast ASCVD incidence rates to inform health care policy development and investments to targeted population. Bayesian age-period-cohort (APC) models were then fitted to the observed data (1990-2021) to project age-standardized rates (with the mid-year 1990 population as the index) for the prevalence and mortality for IHD, stroke, and PAD from 2022 through 2040. Default log-normal priors chosen for each term in the model and the posterior estimates from the model fit were obtained to predict the incidence rates. (Cotton2025?)

Methods

  • Detail the models or algorithms used.

  • Justify your choices based on the problem and data.

The common non-parametric regression model is \(Y_i = m(X_i) + \varepsilon_i\), where \(Y_i\) can be defined as the sum of the regression function value \(m(x)\) for \(X_i\). Here \(m(x)\) is unknown and \(\varepsilon_i\) some errors. With the help of this definition, we can create the estimation for local averaging i.e. \(m(x)\) can be estimated with the product of \(Y_i\) average and \(X_i\) is near to \(x\). In other words, this means that we are discovering the line through the data points with the help of surrounding data points. The estimation formula is printed below (R Core Team 2019):

\[ M_n(x) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} W_n (X_i) Y_i \tag{1} \]\(W_n(x)\) is the sum of weights that belongs to all real numbers. Weights are positive numbers and small if \(X_i\) is far from \(x\).

Another equation:

\[ y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 +\varepsilon_i \]

ggplot1 = murders %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x=population/10^6, y=total)) 

  ggplot1 + geom_point(aes(col=region), size = 4) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label=abb)) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  geom_smooth(formula = "y~x", method=lm,se = F)+
  xlab("Populations in millions (log10 scale)") + 
  ylab("Total number of murders (log10 scale)") +
  ggtitle("US Gun Murders in 2010") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Region")+
      theme_bw()
